The code, cleaned and refactored:

```powershell
<#
    This assumes $Output is an array of output lines.
    If you encounter issues, try splitting first with -split '\r?\n'
#>
if (@($Output).Count -gt 1) {
    # Trim last line containing only success/failure message and split into one block per file
    $ErrorList = $Output[0..($Output.Length - 2)] -join '\n' -split '(\n[^|]+\n)'

    foreach ($Entry in ($ErrorList )) {
        $Lines = $Entry -split '\n'
        $File = $Lines[0].Trim()
        $MistakeList = $Lines | Select-Object -Skip 1

        foreach ($Mistake in $MistakeList) {
            if ($Mistake -match '(?<Line>[0-9]+) \| (?<Mistake>[\w ]+)') {
                $Matches.Remove(0)
                $Matches.Add('Filename', $File)

                # Output the object from the regex match with filename
                [PSCustomObject]$Matches
            }
        }
    }
}
```

If you run this on the `mdspell` output sequence you should get usable PSCustomObjects listing file, line number, and the text that it detects containing a misspelling. These you can put into your pester test and output how you wish to show exactly which files and where the problems are. üòÑ
